******
[1] Florida
Date: Tue 26 Jul 2016
Source: Highlands Today [edited]
http://www.highlandstoday.com/hi/local-news/horse-tests-positive-for-eastern-equine-encephalitis-officials-say-20160726/


A horse in Highlands County has tested positive for eastern equine encephalitis, and residents should be aware of mosquito protection measures, the Florida Department of Health in Highlands County said.

Statewide, this is the 15th equine to be reported with eastern equine encephalitis this year [2016] and the 1st for Highlands County.

Most people who become infected with the virus have no apparent illness. Severe cases of eastern equine encephalitis begin with sudden onset of headache, high fever, chills and vomiting. The illness may then progress into disorientation, seizures or coma, the health department said. There is no specific treatment for eastern equine encephalitis.

"If you experience symptoms of this illness, consult with your healthcare provider and take steps to protect yourself against further mosquito bites. Avoiding mosquito bites while you are sick will also help protect others from infection," the department advised. Health officials also reminded residents that "the best way to protect themselves from mosquito-borne illness is to prevent mosquito bites by practicing good drain and cover methods:"

